1
00:00:02,610 --> 00:00:05,010
What are AI agents?

2
00:00:05,010 --> 00:00:07,290
What are the best use cases for them?

3
00:00:07,290 --> 00:00:09,570
And what do we need to start building them?

4
00:00:09,570 --> 00:00:11,330
We're going to answer these questions

5
00:00:11,330 --> 00:00:15,250
in this first lesson of the AI agents for beginners course.

6
00:00:15,250 --> 00:00:18,250
In this course, we're going to take you from concept to code

7
00:00:18,250 --> 00:00:21,890
covering the fundamentals of building AI agents.

8
00:00:21,890 --> 00:00:23,650
And in this short video, it follows along

9
00:00:23,650 --> 00:00:26,810
with the written lesson, including translations

10
00:00:26,810 --> 00:00:29,610
and a code sample that you can find the link to

11
00:00:29,610 --> 00:00:32,090
above and below this video.

12
00:00:32,090 --> 00:00:35,210
Well, let's get started looking at the parts of an AI agent.

13
00:00:35,210 --> 00:00:37,930
And the first part is a large language model,

14
00:00:37,930 --> 00:00:45,470
which powers the reasoning behind our AI agents.

15
00:00:45,470 --> 00:00:48,110
And what we mean by reasoning is being able to identify

16
00:00:48,110 --> 00:00:51,470
a task requested by users, create a plan to complete

17
00:00:51,470 --> 00:00:55,310
that task and perform the actions of that plan.

18
00:00:55,310 --> 00:01:00,660
Next up is memory.

19
00:01:00,660 --> 00:01:04,180
This can be short-term, the context of the conversation

20
00:01:04,180 --> 00:01:07,060
between the user and the agent, or long-term,

21
00:01:07,060 --> 00:01:09,460
which is a collection of data that allows the agent

22
00:01:09,460 --> 00:01:12,580
to improve over time in completing the task.

23
00:01:12,580 --> 00:01:17,820
After that is tools.

24
00:01:17,820 --> 00:01:20,340
This can be different services accessed by APIs

25
00:01:20,340 --> 00:01:23,180
that perform an action, data to help determine

26
00:01:23,180 --> 00:01:26,140
what action to take, or different functions

27
00:01:26,140 --> 00:01:30,100
that we will run to send information to the AI agent.

28
00:01:30,100 --> 00:01:34,890
And combining all of these things,

29
00:01:34,890 --> 00:01:38,290
an agent uses the LLM to recognize the task

30
00:01:38,290 --> 00:01:40,770
of the user would want to complete,

31
00:01:40,770 --> 00:01:42,970
identify what available tools are needed

32
00:01:42,970 --> 00:01:47,090
to complete that task, and memory to gather the information

33
00:01:47,090 --> 00:01:50,610
and data that's needed to complete that task.

34
00:01:50,610 --> 00:01:54,330
A simple, real-world example you do every day, hopefully,

35
00:01:54,330 --> 00:01:55,810
is brushing your teeth.

36
00:01:55,810 --> 00:01:58,650
You need to plan out when and where to do it.

37
00:01:58,650 --> 00:02:01,770
Your tools are your toothbrush and toothpaste.

38
00:02:01,770 --> 00:02:04,170
And you have some in-context memory

39
00:02:04,170 --> 00:02:07,210
of the current status of you brushing your teeth

40
00:02:07,210 --> 00:02:08,810
and long-term memory,

41
00:02:08,810 --> 00:02:11,570
maybe your preferences of toothpaste waiver.

42
00:02:11,610 --> 00:02:13,490
I'm a spearman fan myself.

43
00:02:13,490 --> 00:02:15,170
Thanks for asking.

44
00:02:15,170 --> 00:02:17,010
But we aren't here to brush our teeth.

45
00:02:17,010 --> 00:02:18,650
We're here to build AI agents.

46
00:02:18,650 --> 00:02:20,610
So let's head over to the code to do so.

47
00:02:21,650 --> 00:02:25,290
Okay, so now we're here in our code editor

48
00:02:25,290 --> 00:02:28,410
to run the first code sample attached to lesson one.

49
00:02:28,410 --> 00:02:30,530
In this example, we're going to actually work

50
00:02:30,530 --> 00:02:32,770
with semantic kernel and agentic framework

51
00:02:32,770 --> 00:02:35,170
from Microsoft and GitHub models,

52
00:02:35,170 --> 00:02:38,450
which gives us free access to large language models.

53
00:02:38,450 --> 00:02:40,690
If this is the first time you've seen a Jupyter notebook

54
00:02:40,690 --> 00:02:43,010
or if you want to learn how to get set up,

55
00:02:43,010 --> 00:02:46,450
we actually have a chapter dedicated to setting this up

56
00:02:46,450 --> 00:02:48,610
and running the code in the course.

57
00:02:48,610 --> 00:02:50,530
But we won't focus too much on specifics

58
00:02:50,530 --> 00:02:52,570
of semantic kernel in this lesson,

59
00:02:52,570 --> 00:02:54,530
as the next chapter will be a focus

60
00:02:54,530 --> 00:02:56,450
on the different agentic frameworks,

61
00:02:56,450 --> 00:02:59,450
how they work and their differences and benefits.

62
00:02:59,450 --> 00:03:01,010
But the first thing I want to point you to

63
00:03:01,010 --> 00:03:04,370
is this class destinations plugin.

64
00:03:04,370 --> 00:03:07,530
This is basically where we start to list the functions

65
00:03:07,530 --> 00:03:11,530
or tools that we basically want the agent to being called.

66
00:03:11,530 --> 00:03:15,410
In this case, we have an agent that has an availability

67
00:03:15,410 --> 00:03:16,970
of different, a list basically

68
00:03:16,970 --> 00:03:19,610
of different destinations around the world.

69
00:03:19,610 --> 00:03:22,330
And we also have a function that makes it

70
00:03:22,330 --> 00:03:23,930
that each time you call it,

71
00:03:23,930 --> 00:03:27,130
it will choose a random city out of that list

72
00:03:27,130 --> 00:03:30,570
and give it to the user or basically return it.

73
00:03:30,570 --> 00:03:33,370
So we're going to, again, not really focus too much

74
00:03:33,370 --> 00:03:35,170
exactly on how semantic kernel is working,

75
00:03:35,170 --> 00:03:37,250
but this is the syntax of adding that plugin

76
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:39,290
or adding that tool, like we explained earlier,

77
00:03:39,290 --> 00:03:42,290
agents have access to, on to that agent,

78
00:03:42,290 --> 00:03:44,570
as well as assigning the large language model,

79
00:03:44,570 --> 00:03:47,890
which in this case, I'm going to use GPT-40 mini.

80
00:03:47,890 --> 00:03:50,250
Feel free to experiment with different large language models

81
00:03:50,250 --> 00:03:51,450
and see how they react.

82
00:03:52,650 --> 00:03:55,650
So we're going to go ahead and now go to the code.

83
00:03:55,650 --> 00:03:58,490
We're going to actually simulate a little bit of difference

84
00:03:58,490 --> 00:04:01,410
like of how a user would be interacting with this agent.

85
00:04:01,410 --> 00:04:04,290
So the first thing is they're going to ask for a day trip.

86
00:04:04,290 --> 00:04:06,450
And I think this kind of really illustrates

87
00:04:06,450 --> 00:04:09,290
some of the powers of working with large language models

88
00:04:09,290 --> 00:04:12,130
is a user can kind of communicate in natural language

89
00:04:12,130 --> 00:04:14,650
and not to say I want a vacation, for example,

90
00:04:14,650 --> 00:04:16,210
but a day trip in a large language model

91
00:04:16,210 --> 00:04:19,330
should be able to interpret that this is asking

92
00:04:19,330 --> 00:04:22,250
or maybe requiring the calling this function,

93
00:04:22,250 --> 00:04:24,170
this random destinations, because again,

94
00:04:24,170 --> 00:04:27,050
the user has not really provided a specific city.

95
00:04:27,050 --> 00:04:29,370
And the large language model is aware of

96
00:04:29,370 --> 00:04:33,530
how, what tools are being assigned to it.

97
00:04:33,530 --> 00:04:35,130
And then we're going to also play

98
00:04:35,130 --> 00:04:36,850
with a little bit of the memory itself

99
00:04:36,850 --> 00:04:38,090
by allowing the user to say

100
00:04:38,090 --> 00:04:40,050
they don't like that first destination

101
00:04:40,050 --> 00:04:42,210
and they should plan another vacation.

102
00:04:42,210 --> 00:04:44,890
So if the agent has context, again,

103
00:04:44,890 --> 00:04:47,210
that in context of the memory of the conversations,

104
00:04:47,210 --> 00:04:51,090
it should not repeat itself on the vacation destination.

105
00:04:52,810 --> 00:04:56,530
So if we go into this now interaction,

106
00:04:56,530 --> 00:04:59,610
we can see the user saying plan me a day trip

107
00:04:59,610 --> 00:05:02,850
and then the travel agent comes in and suggests Sydney.

108
00:05:02,850 --> 00:05:05,810
So again, to confirm Sydney is a part of the list

109
00:05:05,810 --> 00:05:07,490
of vacation destinations

110
00:05:07,490 --> 00:05:09,930
that we have assigned into the function.

111
00:05:09,930 --> 00:05:12,290
The user says they don't really like this destination

112
00:05:12,290 --> 00:05:13,730
and plan me another vacation.

113
00:05:13,730 --> 00:05:17,650
So sorry, anyone watching from Sydney.

114
00:05:17,650 --> 00:05:20,290
But then again, though, the agent comes back

115
00:05:20,290 --> 00:05:23,090
and plans a nice trip to Rio de Janeiro,

116
00:05:23,090 --> 00:05:24,650
very similar format.

117
00:05:24,650 --> 00:05:26,970
So again, you can see that the agent

118
00:05:26,970 --> 00:05:29,090
is operating with that function

119
00:05:29,090 --> 00:05:30,250
that returns to the cities.

120
00:05:30,250 --> 00:05:31,730
So it's not just pulling it

121
00:05:31,730 --> 00:05:34,050
from every city it's aware of.

122
00:05:34,050 --> 00:05:36,330
And it also is working with the context memory

123
00:05:36,330 --> 00:05:39,170
to know what the conversation is happening

124
00:05:39,170 --> 00:05:41,170
and displaying an alternative.

125
00:05:41,170 --> 00:05:42,370
So wherever you are,

126
00:05:42,370 --> 00:05:44,970
I hope you enjoy your trip to Sydney,

127
00:05:44,970 --> 00:05:46,290
or Rio de Janeiro,

128
00:05:46,290 --> 00:05:49,210
but our trip on this journey in AI Agents Beginners

129
00:05:49,210 --> 00:05:51,170
goes to lesson two where we'll explore

130
00:05:51,170 --> 00:05:53,250
the different agentic frameworks out there.

131
00:05:53,250 --> 00:05:54,450
See you in the next one.

